The article discusses the history and significance of Thanksgiving in the United States. It mentions how Thanksgiving has been celebrated in both good and tough times throughout the nation's history. It highlights examples such as the Pilgrims celebrating their first successful harvest and the support they received from the Wampanoag people, General George Washington and his troops celebrating Thanksgiving during the battle for independence, and President Abraham Lincoln proclaiming Thanksgiving a national holiday during the Civil War. The article also emphasizes the importance of gratitude and unity, acknowledging the hardships faced by some individuals and expressing support for them. It mentions the various groups of people who contribute to the greatness of the nation, such as service members, first responders, healthcare professionals, teachers, and parents. The article concludes by expressing gratitude for the nation and proclaiming November 23, 2023, as a National Day of Thanksgiving.